      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the student loan principal and interest dance is a bit like a merry-go-round in a magical forest. As you pay off your loan, the principal — the main amount you borrowed — decreases. But the interest, that pesky little goblin, still gets its cut from the remaining principal. So, even though you're paying the same amount each month, the goblin takes a smaller slice of the pie as the principal shrinks. It's like trying to fill a leaky bucket; the goblin always finds a way to sneak in a little more water. Keep an eye on your statement, and you'll see the principal slowly but surely shrinking, while the interest goblin still takes its share. Keep up the good work, and soon you'll be goblin-free!",
